<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-546-660  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 546 660.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Digital Review  August 21 1989 v6 n33 p12(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Buyout may signal wider scope for T3 technology. (SynchronousOptical Network standard; Timeplex acquires Broadband TelesystemsandM;)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Gianatasio, David.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Timeplex Inc. (acquisitions and mergers)Broadband Telesystems Inc. (acquisitions and mergers).andO;Topic:     ConnectivityData CommunicationsFiber OpticsProtocolStandardizationAcquisition.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Buyout May Signal Wider Scope for T3 TechnologyandM;WOODCLIFF LAKE, N.J.andP;  -- The Synchronous Optical Network (Sonet) standard,representing wide area fiber-optic networking technology, may move closer towide acceptance if a proposed acquisition comes to fruition.andM;Timeplex, a subsidiary of systems giant Unisys, has agreed to acquirePleasanton, Calif.'s Broadband Telesystems, a start-up developer of T3networking products, for an undisclosed sum.andM;Timeplex expects that T3 signals, which company officials describe as the&quot;building blocks&quot; of backbone networks, will &quot;evolve&quot; into Sonet transportsignals.andM;Victoria Brown, Timplex's president, said the T3 market &quot;will mirror the T1market in its evolution from point-to-point to full networking.&quot;andP;  She saidthe acquisition, subject to the approval of Broadband's stockholders, willenable Timeplex users to &quot;migrate to the Sonet standard when it becomeswidely available.&quot;andM;Sonet comprises a set of optical transmission rates, transmission signals,and optical interfaces, and a multiplexing hierarchy.andP;  Sonet-based networksare able to move large amounts of voice, data and image information indigital form through glass fiber cables that enable multivendor equipment tocommunicate.andM;Sonet technology handles very high-speed transmission rates exceeding 50MBper second.andM;T3 transmission technology allows DS3 signals to be sent at the rate of45Mbits per second.andP;  T3, because it can handle the equivalent bandwidth of 28T1 signals, allows companies to move equal amounts of data more quickly at agreater savings than if they were using T1 circuit technology.andM;Brown said the T3 technology being developed by Broadband will be used inTimeplex's bid to establish Sonet as a standard.andO;</TEXT></DOC>